<div id=3D"faq">

<hr>

	<h2>Calculating days between two dates</h2>
	<p>
	If you want to know how many hours, days or weeks there are between one da=
te and another, our online calculator is here to help you.
	</p>
	<p>
	Perhaps you want to find out exactly how old you are, or work out how many=
 days there are until your next birthday. Or, maybe you're looking to calcu=
late the=20
	number of hours or days until you retire. Whatever the reason, you can use=
 this calculator to assist you.=20
	</p>
=09
	<h2>How to calculate weeks between dates</h2>
	<p>
	To calculate the number of weeks between two dates, count the number of da=
ys between the dates and then divide your figure by 7.=20
	</p>
	<p>
	This gives you a total number of weeks including a decimal. To work out th=
e decimal as a number of days, try the following steps:
	</p>
=09
	<ol class=3D"howTo">
	 <li>Work out the number of days between your start date and end date</li>
	 <li>Divide the number of days by 7 to get the number of weeks, with a dec=
imal</li>
	 <li>Separate the figures after the decimal point &amp; convert them to da=
ys by multiplying by 7</li>
	 <li>You now have your answer in whole weeks plus remainder days (part wee=
k)</li>
	</ol>
=09
	<h3>Example calculation for weeks between dates</h3>
	<p>
	Let's say you want to know how many weeks there are between 5th March and =
21st June. We've counted the days and know that there are=20
	108 days between these two dates. Our process to calculate the number of w=
eeks can therefore look like this:
	</p>
=09
	<ol class=3D"howTo">
	 <li>Divide 108 by 7 to get 15.42857. That means 15 whole weeks plus 0.428=
57 of a week</li>
	 <li>Multiply 0.42857 by 7 to get the number of remainder days. 0.42857 =
=C3=97 7 =3D 3 days</li>
	 <li>We have our answer. 15 weeks and 3 days. We can check this using our =
<a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/time/days-between-dates.php#ca=
lcForm" rel=3D"nofollow" title=3D"Scroll up to calculator">calculator</a>.<=
/li>
	</ol>
=09
=09
<!-- Ezoic - Long Content Unit - long_content -->
<div id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-104"></div>
<!-- End Ezoic - Long Content Unit - long_content -->

=09
	<h2>How many days since...?</h2>
	<p>
	Our date calculator allows you to look to the past. You may wish to know h=
ow many days have elapsed since you were born, since you got married=20
	or since a particular date in history (<a href=3D"https://www.thecalculato=
rsite.com/articles/units/how-many-days-since.php#ww2">the end of World War =
II</a>, the birth of Shakespeare?). To calculate the=20
	number of days that have passed, simply enter the year, month and day of t=
he historical date in the first entry on the calculator.=20
	</p>
	<p>
	If you want to look ahead in time, we've got you covered with individual p=
ages telling you the date <a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/time=
/days/30">30 days</a> from today, as well as <a href=3D"https://www.thecalc=
ulatorsite.com/time/days/45">45 days</a> and <a href=3D"https://www.thecalc=
ulatorsite.com/time/days/90">90 days</a>.
	</p>

	<h3>Calculating time manually</h3>
	<p>
	You can, of course, calculate the days or time between two dates manually,=
 and should you wish to go down that route you'll need to remember how many=
 days there are in each month.=20
	We know that there's 365 days in a regular year.=20
	If there's a leap year involved then an extra day is added. A leap year oc=
curs every 4 years and means that February has 29 days instead of 28.
	</p>
	<p>
	Then we get into months and the mnemonic to help remember the number of da=
ys in each:
	</p>

	<blockquote>
	<p>
	"Thirty days have September, April, June, and November. February has 28 al=
one (or 29 in a leap year), And all the=20
	rest have 31."
	</p>
	</blockquote>

	<p>
	So, calculating the number of days between two given dates isn't the easie=
st task because of the way in which our Gregorian calendar works=20
	(we've been using the Gregorian calendar for over 436 years, but=20
	<a href=3D"https://www.vox.com/2016/10/4/13147306/434th-gregorian-calendar=
-anniversary-google-doogle" target=3D"_blank">many people question why we s=
till use it</a>).=20
	</p>

	<p>
	The <b>days between dates calculator</b> on this page works by getting the=
 time stamp of the start date and deducting it from the end date (or vice-v=
ersa if the end date is in the past) before=20
	calculating the number of hours, days and years between them. You can add =
weeks and months to a date by using our <a href=3D"https://www.thecalculato=
rsite.com/time/date-calculator.php">date calculator</a>
	</p>

	<div class=3D"photobox_main">
	<img src=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/images/photos/calculating-da=
ys-between-2-dates.jpg" alt=3D"Calendar and clock representing calculation =
of days and time between 2 dates">
	</div>

	<h2>How many days since I was born?</h2>

	<p>
	To <b>calculate the number of days since you were born</b>, simply enter y=
our date of birth as the <b>start date</b> and then=20
	ensure that the <b>end date</b> is set to today's date (if it isn't alread=
y set, click the 'today' link that appears to the right of the box). Then c=
lick the 'Calculate' button. Alternatively,=20
	you could give my <a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/misc/age-ca=
lculator.php">age calculator</a> a try.
	</p>
	<p>
	As well as telling you how many days you've been on our planet, my calcula=
tor is also able to work out what day you were born on. As an alternative, =
you could=20
	try the <a href=3D"https://www.thecalculatorsite.com/misc/birthday-calcula=
tor.php">birthday calculator</a>, which will show you all sorts of fun fact=
s about your birthday, including the day on which you were born.
	</p>

